What OpenCode currently includes

OpenCode is available as a terminal app, desktop app, and IDE extension. It also supports LSP integration, MCP servers, plugins, custom tools, a JS/TS SDK, and a GitHub automation agent. OpenCode also supports 75+ LLM providers, plus local models, and can use subscriptions like ChatGPT Plus/Pro, GitHub Copilot, and GitLab Duo through its provider flow.

Best setup for you on Windows

For Windows, the docs recommend WSL for the best experience because it gives better compatibility and performance than native Windows. You can still run OpenCode directly on Windows, and the desktop app is available for Windows x64, but the strongest setup is:

WSL + OpenCode CLI + VS Code/Cursor integration + Desktop app + MCP + plugins + SDK.

The “install everything useful” stack
1. Install the CLI

Official options include:

# Windows
choco install opencode
# or
scoop install opencode
# or
npm install -g opencode-ai

The install docs also list Docker and Mise, and note Bun support on Windows is still in progress.

2. Install the desktop app

OpenCode Desktop is in beta and has a Windows x64 build on the official download page / releases.

3. Install the IDE integration

For VS Code, Cursor, Windsurf, or VSCodium, OpenCode’s extension installs automatically when you run opencode in the integrated terminal. There is also a manual marketplace install path. It supports quick-launch shortcuts and shares editor context automatically.

4. Connect your model providers

OpenCode’s docs say to run:

/connect

That lets you authenticate providers, and the docs specifically mention OpenCode’s provider flow plus subscription-based options like ChatGPT Plus/Pro, GitHub Copilot, and GitLab Duo.

5. Initialize each project

Inside your repo:

cd /path/to/project
opencode
/init

That makes OpenCode analyze the project and generate an AGENTS.md file for the repo.

6. Turn on MCP

OpenCode has first-class MCP support. Core commands include:

opencode mcp add
opencode mcp list
opencode mcp auth
opencode mcp debug <name>

OpenCode supports both local and remote MCP servers, and MCP tools become available alongside built-in tools.

7. Use LSP

OpenCode has built-in LSP integration and uses diagnostics to help the model understand your codebase better. The homepage also says it automatically loads the right LSPs.

8. Add plugins

OpenCode supports plugins for extending behavior and integrations. The official ecosystem page lists community plugins for things like ChatGPT Plus/Pro auth, Gemini auth, devcontainers, dynamic context pruning, secret redaction, PTY/background process support, and more. These ecosystem items are community plugins, not core built-ins, so I’d treat them as optional add-ons.

9. Add SDK control

The official SDK package is:

npm install @opencode-ai/sdk

It is a type-safe JS/TS SDK for controlling the OpenCode server programmatically.

10. Add GitHub automation

If you want GitHub issue / PR automation:

opencode github install

The docs say this sets up the GitHub Actions workflow so you can trigger OpenCode from comments like /opencode or /oc.

Commands worth enabling right away

These are especially useful if you want the “full power” setup:

opencode
opencode run "your prompt"
opencode serve
opencode session list
opencode models --refresh
opencode auth list
opencode mcp add
opencode mcp list
opencode github install

opencode serve is useful because the docs say you can attach opencode run to a running server to avoid MCP cold starts. opencode models --refresh updates the cached model list.

